# Failure Capture Protocol

When a test fails, capture evidence before changing the application state.

## Required Failure Evidence

Capture:

- screenshot
- current URL
- page title or heading
- exact failing step
- expected result
- actual result
- console errors
- failed network requests
- request and response snippets
- test data used
- browser and viewport
- reproduction notes
- whether the failure is consistent or intermittent
- related requirement ID or test case ID

## Screenshot Naming

Use:

```text
FAIL-TC-{case_id}-{short-feature}-{YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS}.png
```

Store in:

```text
qa-artifacts/screenshots/
```

## Console Log Naming

Use:

```text
TC-{case_id}-console-{YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS}.txt
```

Store in:

```text
qa-artifacts/console-logs/
```

## Network Log Naming

Use:

```text
TC-{case_id}-network-{YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS}.json
```

Store in:

```text
qa-artifacts/network-logs/
```

Include:

- URL
- method
- status code
- request payload summary
- response body summary truncated to a safe length
- timing when available

Do not store sensitive tokens, passwords, or private user data in artifacts.

## Trace Naming

Use:

```text
TC-{case_id}-trace-{YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS}.zip
```

Store in:

```text
qa-artifacts/traces/
```

Use traces for:

- flaky behavior
- intermittent failures
- complex multi-step failures
- navigation failures
- network race conditions

